WEBVTT

1
00:00:30.291 --> 00:00:33.468
<i>Last season on</i>
Star Trek: Strange New Worlds...

2
00:00:33.642 --> 00:00:35.296
<i>Do you really
still believe our futures</i>

3
00:00:35.470 --> 00:00:36.558
<i>are written in stone?</i>

4
00:00:36.732 --> 00:00:38.038
<i>All I know is that</i>

5
00:00:38.212 --> 00:00:40.344
<i>I'm not ready to let you go.</i>

6
00:00:40.518 --> 00:00:42.564
<i>Everything that happened to me</i>

7
00:00:42.825 --> 00:00:43.825
was so I could do this.

8
00:00:43.869 --> 00:00:45.001
No. this is... Marie...

9
00:00:45.175 --> 00:00:46.568
It's my destiny.

10
00:00:46.785 --> 00:00:48.874
<i>You. of all people.
can understand that.</i>

11
00:00:49.136 --> 00:00:51.505
<i>You have to tell me why things
are so weird with you and Spock.</i>

12
00:00:51.529 --> 00:00:53.638
<i>Spock and I made it very clear
with each other... no labels.</i>

13
00:00:53.662 --> 00:00:57.579
<i>no complicated expectations.
just fun times.</i>

14
00:00:57.753 --> 00:00:59.363
<i>Is this</i>

15
00:00:59.537 --> 00:01:01.235
a "hit it" situation?

16
00:01:01.409 --> 00:01:03.193
It's a new future.

17
00:01:03.367 --> 00:01:05.674
It's whatever kind of adventure
we want it to be.

18
00:01:14.117 --> 00:01:17.773
<i>Captain's personal log.
Stardate 2491.5.</i>

19
00:01:18.034 --> 00:01:20.515
<i>We're at the end of
a routine mission on Tulaxar...</i>

20
00:01:20.776 --> 00:01:23.996
<i>our 15th in a row...
and if I'm being honest.</i>

21
00:01:24.171 --> 00:01:26.564
<i>this may well be
my favorite part.</i>

22
00:02:20.357 --> 00:02:22.272
Were you followed?

23
00:02:22.446 --> 00:02:24.274
-No. sir.
-And the meds?

24
00:02:24.448 --> 00:02:26.668
Handed off more than enough
to save the planet.

25
00:02:26.842 --> 00:02:28.017
Any issues being discovered?

26
00:02:28.278 --> 00:02:29.453
Nothing I couldn't handle.

27
00:02:29.627 --> 00:02:31.238
Four of the ones she drank with

28
00:02:31.499 --> 00:02:33.240
might need a day or two
to sleep it off.

29
00:02:33.414 --> 00:02:35.155
Lightweights.

30
00:02:36.852 --> 00:02:37.592
<i>Captain. we are in position.</i>

31
00:02:37.766 --> 00:02:39.071
<i>Ready to beam you up</i>

32
00:02:39.376 --> 00:02:40.614
<i>-on your order.</i>
-Copy that. Number One.

33
00:02:40.638 --> 00:02:42.466
You know what?

34
00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:44.425
We. uh...

35
00:02:46.253 --> 00:02:48.342
we might ride a little more.

36
00:02:48.603 --> 00:02:50.779
<i>If you say so. Captain.</i>

37
00:02:50.953 --> 00:02:54.174
You know. just to be safe.

38
00:02:54.435 --> 00:02:56.785
Hyah.

39
00:03:13.410 --> 00:03:14.629
Welcome back. Captain.

40
00:03:14.890 --> 00:03:16.084
I can take
your saddle. if needed.

41
00:03:16.108 --> 00:03:17.108
Well. I. uh.

42
00:03:17.153 --> 00:03:18.763
prefer to carry my own gear.

43
00:03:18.937 --> 00:03:20.591
But thanks. Spock.

44
00:03:20.765 --> 00:03:22.202
But you knew that already.

45
00:03:22.376 --> 00:03:23.725
I felt it important to be here

46
00:03:23.899 --> 00:03:25.299
as soon as you returned
to the ship.

47
00:03:25.466 --> 00:03:27.946
You wanted to see me
in my outfit. didn't you?

48
00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:30.253
Perhaps.

49
00:03:35.867 --> 00:03:38.348
Follow me
to my quarters. Mr. Spock.

50
00:03:38.522 --> 00:03:41.003
These boots
are hard to take off alone.

51
00:03:42.874 --> 00:03:44.789
Six months. Chris. nonstop.

52
00:03:44.963 --> 00:03:47.009
That's a lot
of missions in a row.

53
00:03:47.183 --> 00:03:48.576
I'm just worried the crew

54
00:03:48.793 --> 00:03:50.473
is starting to feel
the strain. that's all.

55
00:03:50.534 --> 00:03:53.972
Look. they came to <i>Enterprise</i>
to see things. to...

56
00:03:54.146 --> 00:03:56.410
do things.

57
00:03:56.671 --> 00:03:59.413
And the more you see
and do in the moment.

58
00:03:59.587 --> 00:04:03.199
the less you have to think
about the past. right?

59
00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:07.595
We all need weekends
once in a while.

60
00:04:07.856 --> 00:04:09.423
Even you.

61
00:04:10.206 --> 00:04:11.816
Understood. Number One.

62
00:04:11.990 --> 00:04:15.690
Not to mention. as much
as I enjoy having the conn.

63
00:04:15.864 --> 00:04:18.649
I wouldn't mind a little time
on-planet once in a while.

64
00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:20.477
Next mission. I promise.

65
00:04:20.651 --> 00:04:22.871
That might be
sooner than you think.

66
00:04:23.045 --> 00:04:26.353
Admiral April
is on his way to see you.

67
00:04:29.399 --> 00:04:30.574
I told you. Bob.

68
00:04:30.748 --> 00:04:32.924
I'm not looking for a promotion.

69
00:04:33.098 --> 00:04:34.404
Well. regardless of intent.

70
00:04:34.578 --> 00:04:36.537
you're being considered for one.

71
00:04:36.711 --> 00:04:38.539
To commodore.

72
00:04:38.713 --> 00:04:40.410
And that. as we both know.

73
00:04:40.584 --> 00:04:42.499
is a stepping stone.

74
00:04:44.327 --> 00:04:48.113
Look. I felt the same way
when I was captain.

75
00:04:48.288 --> 00:04:49.568
You just need to think about it.

76
00:04:49.724 --> 00:04:52.335
Really think.

77
00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:55.382
You just might
surprise yourself.

78
00:04:57.558 --> 00:04:59.473
How long do I have to consider?

79
00:04:59.647 --> 00:05:02.084
We'll need an answer when you
get back from the next mission.

80
00:05:02.258 --> 00:05:04.216
Where are you sending us?

81
00:05:07.176 --> 00:05:09.178
This is a fun one.

82
00:05:11.702 --> 00:05:12.921
Really?

83
00:05:15.967 --> 00:05:17.447
You haven't heard
the constant noises?

84
00:05:17.621 --> 00:05:19.841
Scotty acts like every time
I steer the ship.

85
00:05:20.015 --> 00:05:23.279
it makes his job harder.
so he added endless beeping

86
00:05:23.453 --> 00:05:26.282
to literally make my job harder.

87
00:05:28.371 --> 00:05:29.938
Are you listening?

88
00:05:31.069 --> 00:05:35.073
Sorry. I just have to get
prepared for my mentee training.

89
00:05:35.335 --> 00:05:38.990
Right. your new Academy cadet.

90
00:05:39.164 --> 00:05:40.340
When I got to <i>Enterprise.</i>

91
00:05:40.557 --> 00:05:42.690
I didn't know
anything about anything.

92
00:05:42.864 --> 00:05:44.300
and all of you helped me.

93
00:05:44.561 --> 00:05:46.365
I just want to pass
that on to the next person.

94
00:05:46.389 --> 00:05:50.350
I've been practicing my Vulcan
with Spock to improve it.

95
00:05:56.704 --> 00:05:58.532
<i>Taz Nyota Uhura dwi-mâsh.</i>

96
00:05:58.706 --> 00:06:00.751
<i>Tan-fi bo-shish
ner gab-no-vet âs</i>

97
00:06:00.925 --> 00:06:02.076
<i>dwoz nufezh po nen lhi-de-mosh.</i>

98
00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:04.320
Please do not speak Vulcan.

99
00:06:04.494 --> 00:06:06.583
Your accent is improper.

100
00:06:06.757 --> 00:06:10.718
I thought I got that right.

101
00:06:11.632 --> 00:06:13.721
I am fully versed
in all human dialects.

102
00:06:13.895 --> 00:06:16.550
That is all that is required
for us to communicate.

103
00:06:18.290 --> 00:06:20.467
Right. Let me start again.

104
00:06:20.728 --> 00:06:24.122
I am Ensign Uhura. but you
can call me Nyota. if you like.

105
00:06:24.296 --> 00:06:25.936
I was at the Academy
just a few years ago.

106
00:06:26.037 --> 00:06:27.778
so I know exactly
how you must feel.

107
00:06:28.039 --> 00:06:31.695
You are several years older
than I am.

108
00:06:31.869 --> 00:06:33.436
and since you are human.
it is unlikely

109
00:06:33.610 --> 00:06:35.003
you know how I feel.

110
00:06:35.351 --> 00:06:36.546
Were you present
for the <i>K'thonia</i> disaster?

111
00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:38.006
Or the <i>FFakisha</i> conflict?

112
00:06:38.963 --> 00:06:40.574
That all happened after I left.

113
00:06:40.835 --> 00:06:42.445
Your Vulcan
is poorly pronounced.

114
00:06:42.706 --> 00:06:45.143
your time at the Academy was
completely different than mine.

115
00:06:45.317 --> 00:06:48.190
It appears we do not have
many shared experiences at all.

116
00:06:59.941 --> 00:07:02.073
This is an unusual mission.

117
00:07:02.247 --> 00:07:04.685
We are to face a category ten
interstellar squall.

118
00:07:04.859 --> 00:07:06.659
something we rarely see
in the Alpha Quadrant.

119
00:07:06.730 --> 00:07:08.297
I-I've seen one once.

120
00:07:08.471 --> 00:07:10.908
a long time ago.
but not from this close.

121
00:07:11.082 --> 00:07:14.869
I think I was
in a phone box at the time.

122
00:07:15.043 --> 00:07:17.785
Such distortions
are often briefly occurring.

123
00:07:18.046 --> 00:07:20.570
This one has appeared
around the star Ithaxus.

124
00:07:20.744 --> 00:07:22.137
No explanation.

125
00:07:22.485 --> 00:07:23.897
Doesn't look like it's safe
for us to get near it.

126
00:07:23.921 --> 00:07:25.314
Any inhabited planets

127
00:07:25.488 --> 00:07:26.808
nearby
we should be worried about?

128
00:07:26.924 --> 00:07:27.924
None.

129
00:07:28.056 --> 00:07:29.187
Thank goodness.

130
00:07:29.536 --> 00:07:31.165
And that's the key element
of this mission.

131
00:07:31.189 --> 00:07:32.713
No one we have to protect.

132
00:07:32.930 --> 00:07:35.890
We are here to observe
an unusual stellar display.

133
00:07:36.064 --> 00:07:37.108
That is all.

134
00:07:37.282 --> 00:07:38.327
Oh. it sounds like

135
00:07:38.501 --> 00:07:40.024
we're going to the theater.

136
00:07:40.285 --> 00:07:41.809
Minus the Playbill.

137
00:07:41.983 --> 00:07:43.375
A theater that would likely tear

138
00:07:43.550 --> 00:07:44.831
our ship into small particles
of subspace

139
00:07:44.855 --> 00:07:46.248
should we get too close.

140
00:07:46.553 --> 00:07:48.052
Come on. Mr. Spock.
Where's your sense of adventure?

141
00:07:48.076 --> 00:07:49.773
Perhaps I did not
clearly state the part

142
00:07:49.947 --> 00:07:52.341
about being torn into
small particles of subspace.

143
00:07:53.168 --> 00:07:58.129
Interstellar storms
are like space-time gone wild.

144
00:07:58.303 --> 00:08:01.176
the very stuff of the universe.

145
00:08:01.437 --> 00:08:02.786
Don't you think a glimpse

146
00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:05.006
is worth a little risk?

147
00:08:05.180 --> 00:08:08.096
See? Now. that's the spirit.

148
00:08:25.330 --> 00:08:26.897
Keep us at arm's length. Erica.

149
00:08:27.071 --> 00:08:28.899
Aye. sir.

150
00:08:29.073 --> 00:08:30.553
Very long arms.

151
00:08:30.814 --> 00:08:32.599
I wish we could
get closer. though.

152
00:08:32.773 --> 00:08:35.340
It's absolutely stunning.

153
00:08:35.515 --> 00:08:36.690
I understand the feeling.

154
00:08:36.864 --> 00:08:40.084
To actually see
something like this.

155
00:08:41.259 --> 00:08:43.827
Digital data is more relevant.

156
00:08:44.915 --> 00:08:46.438
Sensors are active.

157
00:08:46.700 --> 00:08:48.068
-Data is cogent.
-If you had to give up

158
00:08:48.092 --> 00:08:49.612
seeing this kind of thing
all the time.

159
00:08:49.703 --> 00:08:51.226
would you miss it?

160
00:08:51.487 --> 00:08:54.011
Every day.

161
00:08:55.143 --> 00:08:56.579
Yeah.

162
00:09:08.025 --> 00:09:10.158
Sir. I'm getting a comm signal.

163
00:09:10.332 --> 00:09:12.639
-Location. Nyota?
-The signal's erratic.

164
00:09:12.813 --> 00:09:16.556
but it seems to be coming
from inside the storm.

165
00:09:16.730 --> 00:09:18.035
It's a mayday. sir.

166
00:09:18.209 --> 00:09:20.777
A ship is stuck
inside the storm?

167
00:09:20.951 --> 00:09:22.518
That's what the signal's saying.

168
00:09:22.692 --> 00:09:24.041
Take us closer. Erica.

169
00:09:24.215 --> 00:09:25.565
But keep your foot
on the brakes.

170
00:09:25.739 --> 00:09:26.914
Understood. Captain.

171
00:09:31.875 --> 00:09:34.138
Not now. Scotty.

172
00:09:56.770 --> 00:09:58.728
Deeper scans suggest
signal origin

173
00:09:58.902 --> 00:10:00.382
is a buoy inside of the storm.

174
00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:02.384
-A buoy?
-It's a starship distress buoy.

175
00:10:02.558 --> 00:10:04.125
but I can't get
a lock on the signal.

176
00:10:04.299 --> 00:10:06.127
Any sign of the source
of the buoy? Any ships?

177
00:10:06.301 --> 00:10:08.303
Scanning. Captain.

178
00:10:12.263 --> 00:10:13.787
Uh-oh.

179
00:10:13.961 --> 00:10:15.761
The storm is undergoing
exponential expansion.

180
00:10:15.789 --> 00:10:17.094
You think?

181
00:10:17.442 --> 00:10:19.282
-Reverse course. Erica. fast.
-Already on it.

182
00:10:52.913 --> 00:10:54.392
We have life support.

183
00:10:54.654 --> 00:10:57.004
Unfortunately. that is
the extent of the good news.

184
00:10:57.178 --> 00:10:59.789
No weapons functionality. Zero.

185
00:10:59.963 --> 00:11:01.182
Long-range comms are down.

186
00:11:01.443 --> 00:11:02.574
Transporters are offline.

187
00:11:02.749 --> 00:11:04.881
Not sure when they'll
be fixed. or if.

188
00:11:05.055 --> 00:11:07.188
We have only the barest amount

189
00:11:07.449 --> 00:11:09.581
of impulse power. For now.

190
00:11:09.843 --> 00:11:11.932
-Warp?
-Out of the question.

191
00:11:12.106 --> 00:11:13.498
Look. our problem is.

192
00:11:13.673 --> 00:11:15.152
we lost all our iridium.

193
00:11:15.326 --> 00:11:17.241
Without it. we can't ignite
the warp engines.

194
00:11:17.415 --> 00:11:19.113
We're basically stuck here.

195
00:11:19.287 --> 00:11:20.723
And do we know where "here" is?

196
00:11:20.984 --> 00:11:22.384
All we've been able
to determine is.

197
00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:23.700
the stellar storm somehow pulled

198
00:11:23.857 --> 00:11:25.293
the ship into a warp field.

199
00:11:25.554 --> 00:11:27.474
The stars aren't lining up
to give us a location.

200
00:11:27.556 --> 00:11:29.447
but we think it's just the main
computer coming back on line.

201
00:11:29.471 --> 00:11:30.994
Okay.

202
00:11:32.213 --> 00:11:34.493
Deploy a locator and send
out a mayday. Let's use a flare.

203
00:11:34.650 --> 00:11:36.347
-On it.
-Short-range scans

204
00:11:36.521 --> 00:11:38.393
suggest we can only
extrapolate our position.

205
00:11:38.567 --> 00:11:40.177
Of the four planets
scanned so far.

206
00:11:40.351 --> 00:11:41.351
three are M-class.

207
00:11:41.483 --> 00:11:42.789
Inhabited? Anyone who

208
00:11:42.963 --> 00:11:44.723
-might give us a hand?
-Impossible to tell.

209
00:11:44.791 --> 00:11:46.444
given our current
sensor capabilities.

210
00:11:46.706 --> 00:11:49.273
But we have detected iridium
on the nearest M-class planet...

211
00:11:49.447 --> 00:11:51.512
a few hours' journey with
our current impulse engines.

212
00:11:51.536 --> 00:11:53.340
And one of our shuttles
is still functional enough

213
00:11:53.364 --> 00:11:55.366
to get us to the surface.
I think.

214
00:11:57.325 --> 00:11:58.587
Well. Number One.

215
00:11:58.761 --> 00:12:01.677
you wanted a mission
on a strange new world.

216
00:12:01.851 --> 00:12:03.592
Looks like you got one.

217
00:12:04.811 --> 00:12:06.421
Curie. <i>this is Enterprise.</i>

218
00:12:06.595 --> 00:12:08.595
<i>You are now entering
the planet's upper atmosphere.</i>

219
00:12:08.640 --> 00:12:10.730
Heading towards
the last known iridium location.

220
00:12:10.904 --> 00:12:13.036
The land mass
is quite choppy down there.

221
00:12:13.210 --> 00:12:14.810
We're five-by-five.
We might have to land

222
00:12:14.908 --> 00:12:16.126
pretty far from the signal.

223
00:12:16.300 --> 00:12:18.259
There aren't any closer options.

224
00:13:22.453 --> 00:13:24.368
The iridium's over there.

225
00:13:33.203 --> 00:13:36.424
Near what is
definitely a volcano.

226
00:13:49.306 --> 00:13:51.178
Um...

227
00:13:51.439 --> 00:13:54.268
I'm detecting life signs.

228
00:13:55.922 --> 00:13:57.401
What kind of life signs?

229
00:13:57.575 --> 00:13:59.186
Large.

230
00:14:00.100 --> 00:14:01.928
Taller than us?

231
00:14:02.102 --> 00:14:03.277
Much taller.

232
00:14:07.585 --> 00:14:11.938
Is there a way around that?

233
00:14:13.156 --> 00:14:14.331
No.

234
00:14:14.505 --> 00:14:16.507
We want the iridium.

235
00:14:16.681 --> 00:14:20.207
we have to get past that.

236
00:14:27.823 --> 00:14:29.216
Great news.

237
00:14:33.785 --> 00:14:35.178
I've got a fix on the creature.

238
00:14:35.352 --> 00:14:36.919
That's not the problem.
It's. uh...

239
00:14:37.093 --> 00:14:39.182
<i>trying to do something about it.</i>

240
00:14:39.356 --> 00:14:41.228
-Can't you just stun it?
<i>-Well. if I had</i>

241
00:14:41.402 --> 00:14:43.883
<i>phasers. sure. Um...</i>

242
00:14:44.057 --> 00:14:45.493
I might be able to send a bolt

243
00:14:45.754 --> 00:14:47.427
of electricity. but
I don't want to kill the laddie.

244
00:14:47.451 --> 00:14:50.237
We should probably determine
what it can withstand first.

245
00:14:51.455 --> 00:14:53.153
What are you doing?

246
00:15:03.076 --> 00:15:04.381
Why did you just shoot it?

247
00:15:04.555 --> 00:15:06.296
Wha... I was on stun.

248
00:15:06.557 --> 00:15:08.037
And you saw. Nothing happened.

249
00:15:08.255 --> 00:15:09.335
The laddie may be a wee bit

250
00:15:09.386 --> 00:15:10.692
stronger than we anticipated.

251
00:15:10.997 --> 00:15:12.717
"Laddie"? You think
that's what I talk like?

252
00:15:12.781 --> 00:15:14.461
-That's totally -what you talk like.
<i>-Fine.</i>

253
00:15:18.265 --> 00:15:19.919
Something's just
grabbed the ship.

254
00:15:40.591 --> 00:15:42.506
<i>Space.</i>

255
00:15:43.638 --> 00:15:45.640
<i>The final frontier.</i>

256
00:15:47.555 --> 00:15:51.298
<i>These are the voyages
of the starship</i> Enterprise.

257
00:15:52.473 --> 00:15:55.171
<i>Its five-year mission:</i>

258
00:15:55.345 --> 00:15:58.348
<i>to explore strange new worlds...</i>

259
00:15:59.567 --> 00:16:02.874
<i>to seek out new life</i>

260
00:16:03.049 --> 00:16:05.616
<i>and new civilizations...</i>

261
00:16:06.617 --> 00:16:10.621
<i>to boldly go
where no one has gone before.</i>

262
00:17:38.187 --> 00:17:39.754
Where did they come from?

263
00:17:40.146 --> 00:17:41.862
Unclear. Captain.
Our sensors are functioning

264
00:17:41.886 --> 00:17:43.236
below normal parameters.

265
00:17:43.627 --> 00:17:44.454
They seem to have
attached some kind

266
00:17:44.628 --> 00:17:46.369
of energy tendrils.

267
00:17:46.630 --> 00:17:48.086
They are similar to our
tractor beams. but the style

268
00:17:48.110 --> 00:17:49.310
is one I am not familiar with.

269
00:17:49.416 --> 00:17:50.696
Do we have any weapons? Shields?

270
00:17:50.765 --> 00:17:51.983
No. the shields are still

271
00:17:52.375 --> 00:17:54.160
not functioning. Captain.
and Scotty cannot

272
00:17:54.334 --> 00:17:56.553
repair the weapons
without iridium.

273
00:17:56.727 --> 00:17:57.946
We-we are crippled.

274
00:17:58.120 --> 00:17:59.184
They're literally
towing us away.

275
00:17:59.208 --> 00:18:00.368
Do we have impulse? Anything?

276
00:18:00.557 --> 00:18:02.037
No. using impulse engines

277
00:18:02.298 --> 00:18:04.258
would be like trying
to free ourselves from a boat

278
00:18:04.431 --> 00:18:06.346
using a pair of flippers.

279
00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:07.738
Small flippers.

280
00:18:08.043 --> 00:18:09.603
Flippers that could be
lost at any time.

281
00:18:09.740 --> 00:18:11.307
Comms are
still functioning. sir.

282
00:18:11.568 --> 00:18:12.830
As is our universal translator.

283
00:18:13.092 --> 00:18:14.397
Does anyone recognize that ship?

284
00:18:14.571 --> 00:18:15.703
I do not.

285
00:18:15.964 --> 00:18:16.791
and it does not exist
in our database.

286
00:18:16.965 --> 00:18:18.662
Hail them. Nyota.

287
00:18:19.010 --> 00:18:20.640
Let's try the friendly approach
first. We don't have much else

288
00:18:20.664 --> 00:18:22.101
-to work with.
-Hailing them. sir.

289
00:18:22.275 --> 00:18:23.667
This is Captain Christopher Pike

290
00:18:23.928 --> 00:18:25.147
of the starship <i>Enterprise.</i>

291
00:18:25.321 --> 00:18:26.844
You seem to have...

292
00:18:28.019 --> 00:18:32.154
you seem to have accidentally
taken hold of our ship.

293
00:18:33.286 --> 00:18:34.286
Anything?

294
00:18:34.374 --> 00:18:37.028
They're responding. sir.

295
00:18:39.640 --> 00:18:41.250
<i>I am Battle Commander Cassell.</i>

296
00:18:41.424 --> 00:18:43.383
<i>We didn't attach
our tethers by accident.</i>

297
00:18:43.557 --> 00:18:45.646
<i>We seized
your damaged ship as salvage.</i>

298
00:18:45.820 --> 00:18:50.129
<i>Your ship and its resources
are now our property.</i>

299
00:18:51.173 --> 00:18:52.653
Still nothing from the ship.

300
00:18:52.827 --> 00:18:54.655
Scotty said
he'd come right back.

301
00:18:54.829 --> 00:18:56.918
He didn't. Typical.

302
00:18:57.092 --> 00:18:58.267
I don't like it.

303
00:18:58.528 --> 00:19:00.400
We may be on our own.
at least for now.

304
00:19:01.052 --> 00:19:03.098
We need to get a better idea
of what we're facing.

305
00:19:03.272 --> 00:19:04.621
What about the new...

306
00:19:04.795 --> 00:19:06.014
vaporization thingy?

307
00:19:06.188 --> 00:19:07.929
You know what it's called.

308
00:19:08.103 --> 00:19:09.757
Scotty's not even here
to get annoyed.

309
00:19:09.931 --> 00:19:10.971
Just makes me feel better.

310
00:19:11.062 --> 00:19:12.412
The phasers have been modified

311
00:19:12.586 --> 00:19:15.154
with a contained
disintegration function.

312
00:19:15.328 --> 00:19:18.244
We need to get a clear shot
at that copse of trees.

313
00:19:18.418 --> 00:19:21.464
Maybe we can see the "laddie"
that's hiding behind it.

314
00:19:21.638 --> 00:19:22.726
<i>Commander Cassell.</i>

315
00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:25.251
we are members of Starfleet.

316
00:19:26.687 --> 00:19:29.429
Any actions against us
will be seen

317
00:19:29.603 --> 00:19:31.779
as actions against the
United Federation of Planets.

318
00:19:31.953 --> 00:19:33.737
<i>We aren't familiar
with your Starfleet</i>

319
00:19:33.998 --> 00:19:37.132
<i>or Federation. but if you're
in league with the Dol'drm.</i>

320
00:19:37.306 --> 00:19:39.178
<i>we will destroy you.</i>

321
00:19:44.008 --> 00:19:45.096
What?

322
00:19:45.401 --> 00:19:46.707
Be careful
what you say. Captain.

323
00:19:46.881 --> 00:19:48.491
If they are not familiar
with Starfleet.

324
00:19:48.665 --> 00:19:50.319
it is possible
that they are pre-warp.

325
00:19:50.493 --> 00:19:52.428
They may be seizing our ship
to learn about our technology.

326
00:19:52.452 --> 00:19:54.584
which is strictly
against our prime directive.

327
00:19:54.758 --> 00:19:56.195
They have the ship. Spock.

328
00:19:56.369 --> 00:19:57.849
Right now talking
is our only way out.

329
00:19:57.935 --> 00:19:59.415
Allow me to scan it further.

330
00:19:59.676 --> 00:20:01.635
Perhaps you could stall.

331
00:20:03.289 --> 00:20:06.640
We are not familiar
with the Dol'drm.

332
00:20:06.814 --> 00:20:08.337
We're new
to this region of space.

333
00:20:08.511 --> 00:20:10.296
and if you don't know
the Federation.

334
00:20:10.470 --> 00:20:11.862
we also don't know you.

335
00:20:12.036 --> 00:20:13.342
<i>We are at war. Captain.</i>

336
00:20:13.690 --> 00:20:16.040
<i>with a terrible
and destructive enemy.</i>

337
00:20:16.215 --> 00:20:18.129
<i>and as part
of our wartime covenants.</i>

338
00:20:18.304 --> 00:20:21.220
<i>we have seized your ship
as scrap for our war effort.</i>

339
00:20:21.394 --> 00:20:23.613
<i>If you are not aligned
with the Dol'drm.</i>

340
00:20:23.787 --> 00:20:25.833
<i>you will be released
when we return home.</i>

341
00:20:26.007 --> 00:20:27.967
You can't just take our ship
without consequences.

342
00:20:28.183 --> 00:20:31.273
<i>And yet you have shown us none.
This discussion is over.</i>

343
00:20:31.447 --> 00:20:33.275
Commander. we do have weapons.

344
00:20:33.536 --> 00:20:35.843
and Starfleet has more...
a lot more.

345
00:20:36.017 --> 00:20:37.690
Do you really want us
to turn all of them on you

346
00:20:37.714 --> 00:20:39.325
just to prove our point?

347
00:20:43.459 --> 00:20:44.982
Why don't you come aboard?

348
00:20:47.681 --> 00:20:49.813
I can show you myself.
and we can discuss ways

349
00:20:49.987 --> 00:20:52.120
that the Federation
can help you.

350
00:20:54.905 --> 00:20:56.690
<i>I don't think
this will be useful.</i>

351
00:20:57.560 --> 00:21:00.476
<i>But if you have weapons
to show us. personally.</i>

352
00:21:00.650 --> 00:21:01.999
<i>I'll come on board to see them.</i>

353
00:21:02.217 --> 00:21:03.914
That-That's not exactly
what I said. I...

354
00:21:04.088 --> 00:21:05.307
<i>End communication.</i>

355
00:21:06.700 --> 00:21:08.876
Okay. not ideal.

356
00:21:15.578 --> 00:21:17.319
You sure this is going to work?

357
00:21:17.580 --> 00:21:20.235
Not in the slightest.

358
00:21:22.150 --> 00:21:24.021
Well. at least we're talking.

359
00:21:24.195 --> 00:21:26.328
I am afraid
our circumstance is...

360
00:21:27.634 --> 00:21:29.794
slightly more complicated
than we realized. Captain.

361
00:21:29.897 --> 00:21:31.855
I have determined
our current location.

362
00:21:32.987 --> 00:21:36.033
Scans have revealed that
we are in the Sol system.

363
00:21:36.207 --> 00:21:37.513
Sol?

364
00:21:37.687 --> 00:21:39.559
Spock. this
doesn't make any sense.

365
00:21:39.733 --> 00:21:41.430
Three M-class worlds?

366
00:21:41.648 --> 00:21:44.085
The stellar storm created
an incredible amount of energy.

367
00:21:44.259 --> 00:21:46.217
far beyond
what our ship is capable of.

368
00:21:46.392 --> 00:21:50.352
However. where it sent us
is less relevant than when.

369
00:21:52.136 --> 00:21:55.879
Currently. we are
65 million years in the past.

370
00:21:59.796 --> 00:22:03.539
The planet Commander Cassell
is dragging us toward is Mars.

371
00:22:03.713 --> 00:22:05.411
Mars?

372
00:22:06.499 --> 00:22:10.111
Then that would mean the planet
that Una flew the shuttle to...

373
00:22:13.375 --> 00:22:15.421
Is Earth. Captain.

374
00:22:35.615 --> 00:22:37.312
So. according to <i>Enterprise.</i>
we can't harm

375
00:22:37.486 --> 00:22:39.923
any native life because doing so
could wreck the future.

376
00:22:40.097 --> 00:22:42.056
Unfortunately.
the dinosaurs do not share

377
00:22:42.230 --> 00:22:46.277
our temporal prohibitions
when it comes to eating us.

378
00:22:48.149 --> 00:22:49.759
I have an idea.

379
00:22:49.933 --> 00:22:51.650
But I don't think either of you
are gonna like it.

380
00:22:51.674 --> 00:22:52.893
Oh. we are way

381
00:22:53.067 --> 00:22:55.199
-past that.
-Yeah.

382
00:22:55.374 --> 00:22:56.549
What you got. boss?

383
00:22:58.202 --> 00:22:59.421
<i>They have never heard</i>

384
00:22:59.595 --> 00:23:01.205
of Starfleet or the Federation

385
00:23:01.380 --> 00:23:02.816
because neither will exist

386
00:23:03.077 --> 00:23:04.470
for millions of years.

387
00:23:04.731 --> 00:23:06.036
It may be challenging

388
00:23:06.254 --> 00:23:08.299
to form a shared frame
of reference. Captain.

389
00:23:08.474 --> 00:23:10.606
It shouldn't be that different
from any first contact

390
00:23:10.780 --> 00:23:12.216
with a pre-warp species.

391
00:23:12.434 --> 00:23:14.784
Except you invited her
on board your starship.

392
00:23:15.655 --> 00:23:17.091
Yeah. there is that.

393
00:23:17.352 --> 00:23:19.485
Look. by the time
our present comes around.

394
00:23:19.659 --> 00:23:21.443
Mars has been lifeless for eons.

395
00:23:21.617 --> 00:23:23.314
I'm going to wager
that nothing we say here

396
00:23:23.576 --> 00:23:25.055
is going to change the future.

397
00:23:25.273 --> 00:23:27.710
so long as she doesn't leave
the ship with anything material.

398
00:23:27.884 --> 00:23:30.409
Alternatively.
any single one of our actions

399
00:23:30.583 --> 00:23:32.715
could result in
our future never occurring.

400
00:23:32.976 --> 00:23:34.891
Okay. so out of
an abundance of caution.

401
00:23:35.152 --> 00:23:36.415
we'll keep her from...

402
00:23:36.589 --> 00:23:37.720
Everything?

403
00:23:37.981 --> 00:23:39.418
It feels like
you're not helping.

404
00:23:39.592 --> 00:23:41.942
That's odd.

405
00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:46.033
Scanners seem to have detected
something on the hull.

406
00:23:46.207 --> 00:23:48.383
<i>Possible hull breach
on Deck Seven.</i>

407
00:23:48.557 --> 00:23:49.819
We're on Deck Seven.

408
00:23:49.993 --> 00:23:52.082
No adjustment
in air temperature. Strange.

409
00:23:52.256 --> 00:23:53.040
Where?

410
00:23:53.214 --> 00:23:54.737
Corridor.

411
00:24:03.006 --> 00:24:04.878
Commander Cassell.

412
00:24:14.061 --> 00:24:15.671
I'm Captain Pike.

413
00:24:15.845 --> 00:24:17.760
You are... short.

414
00:24:17.934 --> 00:24:20.981
Our-our planet's
a little heavier than yours.

415
00:24:21.155 --> 00:24:23.984
Hence this unpleasant
artificial gravity on your ship?

416
00:24:24.158 --> 00:24:26.160
-Too unpleasant? We can adjust.
-No need.

417
00:24:26.334 --> 00:24:28.336
We're obviously considerably
stronger than you are.

418
00:24:28.510 --> 00:24:29.859
How did you get inside our ship?

419
00:24:30.033 --> 00:24:31.600
We phased through your wall.

420
00:24:33.472 --> 00:24:35.474
Do you not have
phasing technology?

421
00:24:35.648 --> 00:24:38.825
Well. no. but we have
transporters which allow us...

422
00:24:39.086 --> 00:24:41.436
Which we can gladly discuss
at a later juncture.

423
00:24:41.610 --> 00:24:44.395
Allow me to introduce
our science officer Spock.

424
00:24:44.570 --> 00:24:48.574
Dr. M'Benga.
and our engineer Mr. Scott.

425
00:24:50.663 --> 00:24:51.925
Forgive me if I don't.

426
00:24:52.186 --> 00:24:53.546
My guards
are under standing orders

427
00:24:53.579 --> 00:24:55.232
to kill anyone
who comes too close.

428
00:24:55.494 --> 00:24:56.886
Okay.

429
00:24:58.105 --> 00:25:00.499
I assure you. that
won't be necessary. Commander.

430
00:25:00.673 --> 00:25:02.936
-You're here as our guests.
-We're here as your captors

431
00:25:03.110 --> 00:25:05.547
to see your weaponry.
Captain Pike.

432
00:25:05.721 --> 00:25:07.027
Commander. you are not
our enemy.

433
00:25:07.201 --> 00:25:09.464
That assessment is mine to make.

434
00:25:09.725 --> 00:25:12.380
You would do the same
in my position. would you not?

435
00:25:15.992 --> 00:25:17.951
Our transporter typically
sweeps our visitors

436
00:25:18.125 --> 00:25:19.300
for health and safety.

437
00:25:19.561 --> 00:25:21.607
Would you permit me
to examine you?

438
00:25:21.781 --> 00:25:24.740
To ensure you haven't brought
any pathogens aboard

439
00:25:24.914 --> 00:25:28.309
and that you can handle any
you might find aboard as well.

440
00:25:28.483 --> 00:25:30.920
Well. I am confident
our biological prophylaxis

441
00:25:31.094 --> 00:25:33.749
will keep all parties safe.

442
00:25:33.923 --> 00:25:35.751
However. given I also
trained in medicine.

443
00:25:35.925 --> 00:25:38.362
I am curious
to see what technology you have.

444
00:25:39.494 --> 00:25:42.541
After that. we will see
your weapons systems.

445
00:25:50.549 --> 00:25:52.072
Stun?

446
00:25:52.246 --> 00:25:56.511
Your plan is to get close
and just use stun?

447
00:25:56.772 --> 00:25:58.426
-That is correct.
-I'll remind you.

448
00:25:58.600 --> 00:26:00.428
we tried it.
It didn't faze it one bit.

449
00:26:00.602 --> 00:26:02.014
I mean. we could just
disintegrate it.

450
00:26:02.038 --> 00:26:03.387
if it wasn't for. you know.

451
00:26:03.605 --> 00:26:05.346
the whole "destroy
the entire future" part.

452
00:26:05.520 --> 00:26:07.740
I'm going to get close enough
so it opens its mouth.

453
00:26:07.914 --> 00:26:10.743
shoot in its soft palate.
and hope it works.

454
00:26:11.004 --> 00:26:13.243
And that it doesn't decide
you're maybe a delicious snack

455
00:26:13.267 --> 00:26:14.573
with several more
yummies nearby?

456
00:26:14.747 --> 00:26:16.027
We'll kill it
if it gets to that.

457
00:26:16.096 --> 00:26:17.401
Don't.

458
00:26:17.663 --> 00:26:19.118
We genuinely don't know
the future effects

459
00:26:19.142 --> 00:26:20.448
of anything we might do here.

460
00:26:23.016 --> 00:26:25.932
I'll stun. and then we run.

461
00:26:26.106 --> 00:26:26.933
Crazy.

462
00:26:27.107 --> 00:26:28.456
Dangerous.

463
00:26:28.717 --> 00:26:30.937
Maybe even insane.
But I'm kind of impressed.

464
00:26:31.111 --> 00:26:32.416
Is that weird?

465
00:26:46.126 --> 00:26:47.867
Hey! Dinosaur!

466
00:26:48.041 --> 00:26:50.347
You there!

467
00:27:28.255 --> 00:27:30.518
Did it eat her?

468
00:27:30.692 --> 00:27:31.867
It's not chewing.

469
00:27:33.826 --> 00:27:36.306
It's asleep. Stun worked!

470
00:27:39.614 --> 00:27:41.442
And you didn't kill him.

471
00:27:41.703 --> 00:27:43.009
Nice work.

472
00:27:43.183 --> 00:27:47.143
Let's move. Before <i>she</i> wakes up.

473
00:27:47.317 --> 00:27:49.232
-She?
-Yeah.

474
00:27:49.406 --> 00:27:51.800
It's not a "laddie."
it's a "lassie."

475
00:27:56.370 --> 00:27:58.807
There are many different types
of people on this ship.

476
00:27:58.981 --> 00:28:00.061
In this room alone. we have

477
00:28:00.200 --> 00:28:02.724
humans. Vulcans and Tellarites.

478
00:28:02.898 --> 00:28:04.180
As members of Starfleet.
we've encountered

479
00:28:04.204 --> 00:28:05.205
countless other species.

480
00:28:05.466 --> 00:28:06.989
We come from different planets.

481
00:28:07.163 --> 00:28:08.730
but we have ways
to work together.

482
00:28:08.948 --> 00:28:12.299
And none of these countless
species wish to destroy you?

483
00:28:12.473 --> 00:28:15.432
-Members of the Federation. no.
-Ah.

484
00:28:15.606 --> 00:28:17.826
but I get the feeling others do?

485
00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:19.610
Well. those that don't like us

486
00:28:19.872 --> 00:28:21.545
aren't against just one of us.
they're against all of us.

487
00:28:21.569 --> 00:28:23.397
Our unity is our best deterrent.

488
00:28:23.571 --> 00:28:25.616
Again. because of your weapons?

489
00:28:26.748 --> 00:28:28.924
Federation members do bring
weapons to the table.

490
00:28:29.098 --> 00:28:31.971
but that same unity means we
often do not have to use them.

491
00:28:32.232 --> 00:28:34.408
I must admit.
I have difficulty imagining

492
00:28:34.582 --> 00:28:36.671
such an alliance as this.

493
00:28:36.845 --> 00:28:38.717
Many worlds working together.

494
00:28:38.978 --> 00:28:39.979
Technically. we...

495
00:28:40.153 --> 00:28:41.850
we don't just
work together. we...

496
00:28:42.024 --> 00:28:43.523
we pick up a lot of stuff
from each other.

497
00:28:43.547 --> 00:28:45.288
None of those others

498
00:28:45.462 --> 00:28:48.378
are concerned that you'll turn
their weapons against them?

499
00:28:48.552 --> 00:28:50.772
Sometimes it's just recipes.

500
00:28:50.946 --> 00:28:52.905
Or...

501
00:28:53.079 --> 00:28:54.689
music. Whatever we share.

502
00:28:54.863 --> 00:28:56.822
it tends to add up

503
00:28:57.083 --> 00:28:58.649
to more than
the sum of its parts.

504
00:28:58.824 --> 00:29:00.739
I only know my world

505
00:29:00.913 --> 00:29:02.088
and the Dol'drm.

506
00:29:02.262 --> 00:29:03.916
"Alien" to me means evil.

507
00:29:04.090 --> 00:29:05.221
Humans

508
00:29:05.482 --> 00:29:06.842
have a way of saying.
when it comes

509
00:29:07.006 --> 00:29:08.877
to facing an enemy.
the carrot or the stick.

510
00:29:09.051 --> 00:29:11.053
What is a carrot?

511
00:29:11.227 --> 00:29:13.403
Is it a weapon of some sort?

512
00:29:13.577 --> 00:29:15.797
I imagine it is more persuasive
than a stick.

513
00:29:15.971 --> 00:29:17.625
Yeah. it is.

514
00:29:17.799 --> 00:29:19.298
but not in the way
that you're thinking.

515
00:29:19.322 --> 00:29:20.628
No. um. you eat a carrot.

516
00:29:20.802 --> 00:29:22.151
It's a reward.

517
00:29:22.325 --> 00:29:24.197
Uh. it helps
to form an alliance.

518
00:29:24.371 --> 00:29:26.590
No. the stick
is the only weapon.

519
00:29:27.766 --> 00:29:29.942
So you're benevolent
until that no longer works.

520
00:29:30.116 --> 00:29:31.944
and only then are you hostile?

521
00:29:32.118 --> 00:29:34.642
It's a strategy of sorts.

522
00:29:34.816 --> 00:29:35.948
I'm happy to say

523
00:29:36.209 --> 00:29:37.993
we have no issues
of contamination.

524
00:29:38.167 --> 00:29:39.778
You clearly dedicate
many resources

525
00:29:39.952 --> 00:29:41.083
to this medical facility.

526
00:29:41.257 --> 00:29:43.477
Frankly. it's
something of a wonder

527
00:29:43.651 --> 00:29:46.001
to see so few occupied beds
or injuries.

528
00:29:46.175 --> 00:29:47.742
Captain Pike.

529
00:29:48.090 --> 00:29:51.572
perhaps I have been too quick
to judge you and your crew.

530
00:29:51.746 --> 00:29:53.704
It appears
you are not the enemies

531
00:29:53.966 --> 00:29:55.663
we perceived you to be.

532
00:29:55.837 --> 00:29:57.186
Glad to hear it.

533
00:29:58.013 --> 00:30:00.233
But appearances
can be deceiving.

534
00:30:00.407 --> 00:30:02.191
Do you have this saying. too?

535
00:30:02.365 --> 00:30:04.541
Take me to your weapons systems.

536
00:30:04.715 --> 00:30:08.067
and then I may better
understand what this alliance

537
00:30:08.241 --> 00:30:09.938
with its many points of view

538
00:30:10.112 --> 00:30:12.158
and carrots and sticks
has to offer.

539
00:30:14.595 --> 00:30:16.553
Of course.

540
00:30:17.119 --> 00:30:18.793
<i>Phasers and photon torpedoes
are your ship's primary weapons?</i>

541
00:30:18.817 --> 00:30:20.688
But not the part most used.

542
00:30:20.862 --> 00:30:23.909
I assume you are referring
to defensive systems?

543
00:30:24.083 --> 00:30:26.346
You mentioned
the use of shields.

544
00:30:26.520 --> 00:30:28.000
Our shields are damaged.

545
00:30:28.174 --> 00:30:30.219
Given time.
our engineering station

546
00:30:30.393 --> 00:30:33.309
or our science station will find
ways of repairing our systems.

547
00:30:33.483 --> 00:30:36.573
What is the main purpose
of your science station?

548
00:30:36.747 --> 00:30:38.488
Is it to assess
the vulnerability

549
00:30:38.662 --> 00:30:39.925
of potential enemies?

550
00:30:43.145 --> 00:30:44.799
Science allows us
a broad understanding

551
00:30:45.060 --> 00:30:47.220
of every culture we encounter
so we can share strengths

552
00:30:47.367 --> 00:30:49.388
and compensate for each other's
respective weaknesses.

553
00:30:49.412 --> 00:30:51.092
Understanding other cultures
has allowed us

554
00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:53.503
to advance faster
than if we were alone.

555
00:30:54.853 --> 00:30:56.811
I am sorry for your loss?

556
00:30:57.638 --> 00:30:59.640
You used the word "alone."

557
00:30:59.814 --> 00:31:01.033
Our people

558
00:31:01.424 --> 00:31:04.471
have ten individual words
for such a state.

559
00:31:04.645 --> 00:31:06.734
differentiated
by emotional inflection.

560
00:31:06.908 --> 00:31:08.518
I'm sorry. I don't follow.

561
00:31:08.692 --> 00:31:11.782
Your translating machine
used the word "widower."

562
00:31:13.349 --> 00:31:15.525
And so my condolences.

563
00:31:20.400 --> 00:31:24.273
Our captains are not permitted
relationships during war.

564
00:31:24.447 --> 00:31:29.975
They leave us vulnerable.
too hesitant to sacrifice.

565
00:31:30.149 --> 00:31:32.368
And we have always been at war.

566
00:31:33.282 --> 00:31:35.632
Well. isn't love
part of what we fight for?

567
00:31:38.679 --> 00:31:40.899
If not that. then...

568
00:31:42.117 --> 00:31:44.685
Have you ever seen
my homeworld of Mars?

569
00:31:47.427 --> 00:31:49.733
We are not familiar with
the current condition of Mars.

570
00:31:49.908 --> 00:31:51.561
If the ship's scanners
are repaired.

571
00:31:51.735 --> 00:31:53.694
will you pull it up on-screen?

572
00:31:54.782 --> 00:31:56.044
Please.

573
00:32:03.269 --> 00:32:05.184
-It's beautiful.
-Yes.

574
00:32:05.358 --> 00:32:08.491
But there is something
more important for you to see.

575
00:32:08.665 --> 00:32:11.755
Turn the planet view
173 degrees.

576
00:32:17.848 --> 00:32:19.502
Valles Marineris.

577
00:32:19.720 --> 00:32:23.245
That crater was caused
when the Dol'drm crashed a ship

578
00:32:23.419 --> 00:32:27.336
onto the surface
and fed on our world.

579
00:32:28.947 --> 00:32:30.122
The only way to stop them was

580
00:32:30.296 --> 00:32:33.255
to tear away
the very land around them.

581
00:32:33.429 --> 00:32:35.170
The invaders died.

582
00:32:35.388 --> 00:32:40.610
But that crater and two million
lives is the price we paid.

583
00:32:41.263 --> 00:32:43.483
-That's horrible.
-That's why your discussions

584
00:32:43.657 --> 00:32:45.180
of cultures. of science.

585
00:32:45.354 --> 00:32:47.748
although kind and hopeful.

586
00:32:47.922 --> 00:32:49.228
are not relevant.

587
00:32:49.445 --> 00:32:52.187
What we need to do
is destroy the Dol'drm

588
00:32:52.361 --> 00:32:54.320
before they devour
the rest of our planet

589
00:32:54.494 --> 00:32:56.235
and turn it all
into a red wasteland.

590
00:32:56.409 --> 00:32:58.430
Well. have you ever tried
communicating with the Dol'drm?

591
00:32:58.454 --> 00:33:00.282
We cannot. They are insects.

592
00:33:00.543 --> 00:33:03.503
They do not speak
or reason as we do.

593
00:33:03.677 --> 00:33:07.202
They simply feed
and move forward.

594
00:33:07.376 --> 00:33:08.856
You may have other options.

595
00:33:09.030 --> 00:33:12.555
Some on our planet argued this.

596
00:33:12.729 --> 00:33:15.341
They believed there were
other ways to deal with them.

597
00:33:15.515 --> 00:33:17.908
As they talked. we died.

598
00:33:18.083 --> 00:33:20.650
There's only one thing
that's ever worked.

599
00:33:20.824 --> 00:33:22.304
Force.

600
00:33:23.131 --> 00:33:24.959
What if we
could offer you something

601
00:33:25.133 --> 00:33:26.482
that would work without weapons?

602
00:33:27.875 --> 00:33:30.834
Something only Starfleet's
resources can provide?

603
00:33:33.011 --> 00:33:35.578
The Federation have met maybe

604
00:33:35.752 --> 00:33:38.233
65 different insectoid species.

605
00:33:38.407 --> 00:33:41.236
Of those. 17 of them don't
use sonic communication.

606
00:33:41.410 --> 00:33:42.629
like us.

607
00:33:42.803 --> 00:33:44.544
This is where
xenoanthropology helps.

608
00:33:44.718 --> 00:33:46.304
We've been able to design
multiple systems

609
00:33:46.328 --> 00:33:48.026
that work for creatures
who communicate

610
00:33:48.200 --> 00:33:50.289
using light. touch or.

611
00:33:50.463 --> 00:33:52.856
in one particularly
difficult case. smell.

612
00:33:53.031 --> 00:33:57.122
Which stunk.

613
00:33:57.296 --> 00:34:00.908
But it did allow us.
eventually. to speak with them.

614
00:34:01.996 --> 00:34:03.519
Fascinating.

615
00:34:03.693 --> 00:34:05.130
You keep insisting
it's impossible

616
00:34:05.304 --> 00:34:07.393
to communicate with the Dol'drm.

617
00:34:07.654 --> 00:34:09.458
If we find out we can.
maybe we could find a way

618
00:34:09.482 --> 00:34:10.642
to stop them without weapons.

619
00:34:10.787 --> 00:34:12.485
What if we could end your war?

620
00:34:12.659 --> 00:34:15.836
What if we could
offer them something?

621
00:34:16.010 --> 00:34:18.404
Isn't it worth
a brief consideration?

622
00:34:20.841 --> 00:34:22.408
Brief.

623
00:34:25.715 --> 00:34:27.456
You have an update?

624
00:34:27.674 --> 00:34:29.913
As more systems come on line.
the introduction of variables

625
00:34:29.937 --> 00:34:32.026
still generates
a consistent outcome.

626
00:34:32.287 --> 00:34:34.178
Quantum entanglement
has <i>Enterprise</i> firmly anchored

627
00:34:34.202 --> 00:34:35.769
65 million years in the past.

628
00:34:35.943 --> 00:34:37.051
You're saying we're stuck here?

629
00:34:37.075 --> 00:34:39.642
Yes. And also no.

630
00:34:39.816 --> 00:34:40.880
The nature
of quantum entanglement

631
00:34:40.904 --> 00:34:42.080
could theoretically snap us

632
00:34:42.341 --> 00:34:43.361
right back
to the moment we left.

633
00:34:43.385 --> 00:34:44.386
Well. that seems good.

634
00:34:44.647 --> 00:34:46.388
However. to do so would require

635
00:34:46.562 --> 00:34:48.129
the power equivalent
of a supernova.

636
00:34:48.303 --> 00:34:50.305
the very same amount
that sent us here.

637
00:34:50.479 --> 00:34:52.612
Without it.
we are trapped in the past.

638
00:34:52.786 --> 00:34:54.179
-Less good.
-Indeed.

639
00:34:55.876 --> 00:34:56.916
<i>Captain. Commander Cassell</i>

640
00:34:57.051 --> 00:34:58.357
<i>and her guard have left the lab.</i>

641
00:34:58.531 --> 00:34:59.967
-Where did they go?
<i>-I don't know.</i>

642
00:35:00.272 --> 00:35:01.553
<i>They just phased
through the floor and were gone.</i>

643
00:35:01.577 --> 00:35:03.405
-Engineering.
-Pike to Engineering.

644
00:35:03.579 --> 00:35:04.928
What's happening down there?

645
00:35:05.233 --> 00:35:06.843
<i>That tall. scary Martian lady</i>

646
00:35:07.105 --> 00:35:08.734
<i>just came right through
the bulkhead and took it.</i>

647
00:35:08.758 --> 00:35:10.543
<i>-We couldn't stop her.</i>
-Took what?

648
00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:15.113
<i>The ship's primary
antimatter fuel cell.</i>

649
00:35:15.287 --> 00:35:17.027
Cassell's location keeps moving.

650
00:35:17.202 --> 00:35:19.291
Deck Ten.

651
00:35:19.465 --> 00:35:21.423
Deck Nine.

652
00:35:21.684 --> 00:35:24.339
Deck Eight. She's headed
for her egress point.

653
00:35:29.344 --> 00:35:30.344
I'm not armed.

654
00:35:30.432 --> 00:35:32.782
I just want to talk.

655
00:35:34.567 --> 00:35:35.785
We were helping you.

656
00:35:36.046 --> 00:35:38.310
and now you're taking
our fuel cell? Why?

657
00:35:41.922 --> 00:35:45.099
Captain...

658
00:35:45.273 --> 00:35:47.884
I have been nothing
but honest with you.

659
00:35:48.146 --> 00:35:49.799
And consistent.

660
00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:52.628
You. however.
have not been equally truthful.

661
00:35:52.802 --> 00:35:53.882
What are you talking about?

662
00:35:53.977 --> 00:35:55.588
You spoke to me of Starfleet.

663
00:35:55.762 --> 00:35:57.503
of all that you've achieved.

664
00:35:57.677 --> 00:36:01.550
It was easy to get a sense
of your respect for your values.

665
00:36:01.724 --> 00:36:05.641
your deep feeling for those
you have fought for and loved.

666
00:36:05.815 --> 00:36:07.730
With these things
you were frank.

667
00:36:07.904 --> 00:36:10.994
You also spoke to me
of where you are from.

668
00:36:11.821 --> 00:36:14.389
But you failed to explain when.

669
00:36:15.173 --> 00:36:16.391
Your Federation doesn't exist.

670
00:36:16.565 --> 00:36:18.176
-That's not entirely true.
-Yet.

671
00:36:18.350 --> 00:36:20.482
It doesn't exist yet.

672
00:36:22.397 --> 00:36:23.485
You showed me your computer

673
00:36:23.790 --> 00:36:25.400
so I could speak
with the Dol'drm.

674
00:36:25.574 --> 00:36:28.098
It was simple
to understand from there

675
00:36:28.273 --> 00:36:30.579
how you determine time with it.

676
00:36:30.753 --> 00:36:34.757
Your Federation won't exist
for millions of years.

677
00:36:34.931 --> 00:36:38.108
And by then
my civilization will be gone.

678
00:36:38.283 --> 00:36:39.719
I'm sorry.

679
00:36:39.893 --> 00:36:41.111
Our regulations...

680
00:36:41.329 --> 00:36:43.026
they forbid me
from telling you that.

681
00:36:43.201 --> 00:36:45.377
But that doesn't mean
that we can't find a way

682
00:36:45.638 --> 00:36:47.727
-out of this for both of us.
-Captain.

683
00:36:48.554 --> 00:36:51.383
I understand you are trying
to save your people.

684
00:36:51.557 --> 00:36:53.863
As I am doing for mine.

685
00:36:54.037 --> 00:36:57.389
But we live now.
not in the future.

686
00:36:58.607 --> 00:37:00.566
Your ship's given us
exactly what we need

687
00:37:00.740 --> 00:37:02.698
to win our war.

688
00:37:04.352 --> 00:37:06.136
I'm sorry.

689
00:37:06.311 --> 00:37:07.877
Commander...

690
00:37:44.523 --> 00:37:47.569
This wreckage is apparently
the source of the iridium.

691
00:37:48.918 --> 00:37:51.704
And that's. like.
an alien spaceship.

692
00:37:51.878 --> 00:37:53.793
On Earth.

693
00:37:53.967 --> 00:37:58.972
65 million years before us.

694
00:37:59.146 --> 00:38:01.931
I have to say this
out loud to believe it.

695
00:38:02.105 --> 00:38:05.544
Those burns... a weapon did that.

696
00:38:05.718 --> 00:38:07.285
It was shot down.

697
00:38:07.459 --> 00:38:09.896
-Our Martian friends?
-Mm-hmm.

698
00:38:11.593 --> 00:38:13.116
The iridium's inside.

699
00:38:13.465 --> 00:38:15.684
No life signs. but there
might be an engine compartment.

700
00:38:15.858 --> 00:38:17.251
Wait here.

701
00:38:43.103 --> 00:38:44.626
All these cryobeds?

702
00:38:44.800 --> 00:38:47.063
I think this was a colony ship.

703
00:38:54.767 --> 00:38:57.770
Must have all died on impact.

704
00:39:05.604 --> 00:39:06.822
Reflexes.

705
00:39:06.996 --> 00:39:09.129
They must all be dead.

706
00:39:10.173 --> 00:39:11.392
If they were settlers.

707
00:39:11.653 --> 00:39:14.177
I'm not sure
if I should feel sad or...

708
00:39:15.614 --> 00:39:16.963
relieved.

709
00:39:18.443 --> 00:39:21.054
Whatever the reason
they were in cryosleep.

710
00:39:21.228 --> 00:39:24.449
they were shot down and died
on a planet far from home.

711
00:39:24.710 --> 00:39:26.276
headed who knows where.

712
00:39:26.451 --> 00:39:28.627
They may be
different from us. but...

713
00:39:29.845 --> 00:39:32.108
they wanted to survive. too.

714
00:39:34.328 --> 00:39:35.895
Iridium fuel pod.

715
00:39:36.069 --> 00:39:37.505
The only one
that wasn't damaged.

716
00:39:37.679 --> 00:39:38.941
Let's hope Scotty and Pelia

717
00:39:39.202 --> 00:39:40.029
can jury-rig it
to the <i>Enterprise.</i>

718
00:39:40.203 --> 00:39:41.422
Can we go now. please?

719
00:39:41.596 --> 00:39:43.119
This place
is giving me the creeps.

720
00:39:43.293 --> 00:39:44.773
Yeah.

721
00:40:11.844 --> 00:40:13.976
You just punched it.

722
00:40:14.150 --> 00:40:17.980
Yeah. well. I didn't have time
to shoot it in the mouth. did I?

723
00:40:19.982 --> 00:40:22.637
Well. if you two are finished
just standing here...

724
00:40:25.031 --> 00:40:27.923
<i>SCOTTY [over comms]: Hey. I've managed
to hook up the backup antimatter pod.</i>

725
00:40:27.947 --> 00:40:29.557
<i>You gotta hurry up
with that iridium.</i>

726
00:40:29.731 --> 00:40:32.212
Yeah. yeah. we're coming. Geez.

727
00:40:51.361 --> 00:40:53.712
You punched a dinosaur?

728
00:40:55.278 --> 00:40:56.671
Well.

729
00:40:56.932 --> 00:40:58.238
I'm sure it had it coming.

730
00:41:01.807 --> 00:41:03.243
What is it?

731
00:41:03.591 --> 00:41:06.855
It's just. I broke my hand
and I don't feel any pain.

732
00:41:07.029 --> 00:41:09.118
Well. how is that possible?

733
00:41:09.292 --> 00:41:10.555
It isn't.

734
00:41:10.816 --> 00:41:12.731
The truth is.

735
00:41:12.905 --> 00:41:15.124
I've felt different
for a while now.

736
00:41:15.298 --> 00:41:17.257
I-I've always had
elevated strength and reflexes.

737
00:41:17.518 --> 00:41:19.259
but now it's-it's almost like

738
00:41:19.433 --> 00:41:21.696
my whole body
feels more attuned.

739
00:41:22.610 --> 00:41:23.916
And your mind?

740
00:41:24.090 --> 00:41:25.483
Confused.

741
00:41:25.657 --> 00:41:29.574
Look. I carry
recessive augmented DNA. right?

742
00:41:29.748 --> 00:41:31.445
Now. is it possible that somehow

743
00:41:31.619 --> 00:41:36.363
all I've been through has
activated those recessive genes?

744
00:41:36.537 --> 00:41:39.627
Are you going to try
and take over the galaxy now?

745
00:41:40.541 --> 00:41:41.890
I don't know.

746
00:41:42.238 --> 00:41:45.459
Hey. You may be carrying
enhanced warrior genes.

747
00:41:45.633 --> 00:41:48.462
but it's not who you are.

748
00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:52.945
I've got to go.

749
00:41:57.471 --> 00:42:00.169
Iridium is installed
and ready to function.

750
00:42:00.343 --> 00:42:02.520
as long as we don't want
to double-check it.

751
00:42:02.694 --> 00:42:03.912
Do we need to double-check it?

752
00:42:04.173 --> 00:42:05.760
We need to get a fix
on that Martian ship.

753
00:42:05.784 --> 00:42:08.090
Are you concerned
or are you worried. Mr. Scott?

754
00:42:08.264 --> 00:42:09.265
Just worried. sir.

755
00:42:09.439 --> 00:42:10.789
Good man.

756
00:42:10.963 --> 00:42:12.573
Bridge is coming back on line.

757
00:42:12.747 --> 00:42:14.923
-Long-range sensors?
-Reinitializing.

758
00:42:15.184 --> 00:42:16.751
-Time?
-15 seconds.

759
00:42:16.925 --> 00:42:18.207
Every second could be
getting Commander Cassell

760
00:42:18.231 --> 00:42:19.972
closer to detonating
that antimatter.

761
00:42:20.146 --> 00:42:21.732
Well. I can't get power
to the ship's systems

762
00:42:21.756 --> 00:42:23.236
any faster. Captain.

763
00:42:25.064 --> 00:42:26.944
-Screens are working. Chris.
-Great. How about

764
00:42:27.022 --> 00:42:29.851
-long-range comms?
-On and functioning. sir. Orders?

765
00:42:30.025 --> 00:42:31.984
Connect the Martian ship.

766
00:42:32.245 --> 00:42:33.376
Hailing them.

767
00:42:33.551 --> 00:42:35.553
And initializing
ship-to-ship visuals.

768
00:42:35.727 --> 00:42:37.247
Commander Cassell.
this is Captain Pike

769
00:42:37.380 --> 00:42:38.991
of the USS <i>Enterprise.</i>

770
00:42:40.340 --> 00:42:42.516
I should have told you where...

771
00:42:42.690 --> 00:42:44.649
when we're from.

772
00:42:44.910 --> 00:42:46.801
I should have been honest.
because then you might have

773
00:42:46.825 --> 00:42:48.145
believed me
about everything else.

774
00:42:48.217 --> 00:42:50.045
There are other ways
of solving conflict.

775
00:42:50.219 --> 00:42:51.743
I understand how you...

776
00:42:52.221 --> 00:42:53.962
<i>Captain. you have
lost crew mates?</i>

777
00:42:54.136 --> 00:42:56.225
<i>-Friends?</i>
-Yes. Many.

778
00:42:56.399 --> 00:42:58.706
<i>Imagine those losses
a thousandfold.</i>

779
00:42:58.880 --> 00:43:02.623
<i>Imagine a wound on your planet
that will never heal.</i>

780
00:43:02.797 --> 00:43:06.453
<i>A memorial to millions of dead
etched in rock and blood.</i>

781
00:43:06.627 --> 00:43:10.849
I know you believe
that what you're doing is right.

782
00:43:11.023 --> 00:43:13.547
But I have seen a future
where species can coexist.

783
00:43:13.721 --> 00:43:15.288
<i>And I have seen one
on your computers</i>

784
00:43:15.462 --> 00:43:18.465
<i>where my homeworld
is a barren red wasteland.</i>

785
00:43:19.945 --> 00:43:22.184
<i>Can you tell me the Dol'drm
are not responsible for that?</i>

786
00:43:22.208 --> 00:43:23.775
No. I can't.

787
00:43:23.949 --> 00:43:26.125
But I can tell you
that if you use our technology

788
00:43:26.299 --> 00:43:29.345
to change the future.
millions of lives may be lost.

789
00:43:29.607 --> 00:43:32.087
<i>And millions of lives
may be saved.</i>

790
00:43:32.261 --> 00:43:34.699
<i>The lives of my people.</i>

791
00:43:34.873 --> 00:43:37.266
<i>Isn't that what a captain does?</i>

792
00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:39.442
<i>Save her people?</i>

793
00:43:40.313 --> 00:43:43.359
<i>Wouldn't you?</i>

794
00:43:43.533 --> 00:43:45.753
Uh. she shut off her comms.

795
00:43:46.014 --> 00:43:47.450
And they're not
responding to hails.

796
00:43:47.625 --> 00:43:48.713
-Engines?
-Half-impulse.

797
00:43:48.887 --> 00:43:50.236
Erica. plot an intercept course.

798
00:43:50.410 --> 00:43:51.930
We're gonna try
to stop them from using

799
00:43:52.020 --> 00:43:53.345
-our antimatter.
-The only question is.

800
00:43:53.369 --> 00:43:54.849
where are they planning
to use it?

801
00:43:55.023 --> 00:43:56.784
They don't have warp.
Where is this enemy planet?

802
00:43:56.808 --> 00:43:58.046
Long-range sensors
are fully operational.

803
00:43:58.070 --> 00:44:00.115
Extrapolating their course.

804
00:44:01.073 --> 00:44:02.964
They are headed for
the fifth planet in the system.

805
00:44:02.988 --> 00:44:05.207
-Jupiter?
-No. this planet is much smaller.

806
00:44:05.468 --> 00:44:06.731
Similar to Mars.

807
00:44:07.079 --> 00:44:08.839
At a distance of
480 million kilometers from Sol

808
00:44:08.863 --> 00:44:10.711
and 120 million kilometers
from the Martian solar rotation.

809
00:44:10.735 --> 00:44:13.015
But there's no fifth planet
like that in our solar system.

810
00:44:13.172 --> 00:44:16.915
The planet is populated
by billions of life-forms.

811
00:44:17.089 --> 00:44:19.047
An arachnid species.

812
00:44:19.787 --> 00:44:23.791
That's what we found crashed
on Earth. with the iridium.

813
00:44:25.097 --> 00:44:26.497
The fifth planet
of our solar system

814
00:44:26.664 --> 00:44:27.926
is the Dol'drm homeworld.

815
00:44:28.100 --> 00:44:29.797
Captain. the Martian warship
is approaching

816
00:44:29.971 --> 00:44:32.278
the fifth planet
at high impulse.

817
00:44:32.452 --> 00:44:34.236
On screen.

818
00:44:36.325 --> 00:44:37.675
We will be in firing range

819
00:44:37.936 --> 00:44:39.304
of the Martian ship
in less than one minute.

820
00:44:39.328 --> 00:44:40.408
Phasers aren't working yet.

821
00:44:40.547 --> 00:44:41.940
We just need to disable

822
00:44:42.157 --> 00:44:43.898
the Martian ship.
Can we try a tractor beam?

823
00:44:44.159 --> 00:44:45.267
-There's not enough power at this range.
-Photon torpedoes?

824
00:44:45.291 --> 00:44:46.335
We need something.

825
00:44:46.509 --> 00:44:47.772
-Checking.
-Captain.

826
00:44:48.033 --> 00:44:49.793
my calculations indicate
that if the Martians

827
00:44:49.861 --> 00:44:51.403
detonate our antimatter pod
at their current proximity.

828
00:44:51.427 --> 00:44:53.560
they will be unable
to escape the explosion.

829
00:44:54.561 --> 00:44:56.955
It's her only way
to guarantee a kill shot.

830
00:44:57.129 --> 00:44:58.809
She's gonna sacrifice
her ship and her crew

831
00:44:58.913 --> 00:45:00.262
to destroy the planet.

832
00:45:00.567 --> 00:45:02.177
Captain. I think
we have enough power

833
00:45:02.351 --> 00:45:03.633
-to fire one photon torpedo.
-As soon as we're in range.

834
00:45:03.657 --> 00:45:05.180
The Martian ship just activated

835
00:45:05.354 --> 00:45:07.008
a missile launcher.

836
00:45:10.142 --> 00:45:12.013
They have deployed
the antimatter.

837
00:45:22.545 --> 00:45:24.045
Can we shoot it down
without detonating it?

838
00:45:24.069 --> 00:45:25.263
Yes. but we're still
not in range.

839
00:45:25.287 --> 00:45:26.419
Spock. how long to impact?

840
00:45:26.593 --> 00:45:28.160
-30 seconds.
-Erica.

841
00:45:28.464 --> 00:45:29.833
give it everything you've got.
Push it right to the edge.

842
00:45:29.857 --> 00:45:31.337
-We have to get in range.
-Aye. sir.

843
00:45:31.424 --> 00:45:33.034
Come on. baby. You've got this.

844
00:45:33.208 --> 00:45:34.775
-20 seconds to impact.
-Erica?

845
00:45:34.949 --> 00:45:36.168
Pegging the red line. sir.

846
00:45:36.342 --> 00:45:38.300
There's a reason
for those lights.

847
00:45:38.474 --> 00:45:40.433
-Shut them off. Scotty.
-Sir. we're in range.

848
00:45:40.607 --> 00:45:42.217
Locking photon torpedo
on target.

849
00:45:42.478 --> 00:45:43.760
-12 seconds to impact.
-Target locked.

850
00:45:43.784 --> 00:45:45.177
We've got it. sir.

851
00:45:48.702 --> 00:45:50.312
Captain.

852
00:45:50.486 --> 00:45:52.837
Fire. sir?

853
00:45:57.493 --> 00:45:59.278
Do not fire.
Repeat. do not fire.

854
00:45:59.452 --> 00:46:02.063
-But. sir...
-Captain. that planet's about to be destroyed

855
00:46:02.237 --> 00:46:03.412
by our technology.

856
00:46:03.673 --> 00:46:05.414
Our future's at stake.
We must fire.

857
00:46:05.588 --> 00:46:07.852
You heard my order. Hold fire.
stand down photon torpedo.

858
00:46:08.026 --> 00:46:09.636
Chris. our future
notwithstanding.

859
00:46:09.897 --> 00:46:12.508
we can't just sit here and let
that entire planet be destroyed.

860
00:46:12.682 --> 00:46:14.597
In our future...

861
00:46:15.468 --> 00:46:17.775
there is no fifth planet.

862
00:46:17.949 --> 00:46:19.428
Three seconds.

863
00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:22.910
Two. One.

864
00:46:57.249 --> 00:46:58.816
I'm sorry.

865
00:47:05.648 --> 00:47:07.259
That blast wave's gonna hit us.

866
00:47:07.520 --> 00:47:09.827
But I think I can outrun it.

867
00:47:10.001 --> 00:47:11.654
No. We should not run.

868
00:47:11.829 --> 00:47:13.569
We need to head
into the blast wave.

869
00:47:13.743 --> 00:47:15.136
Head into that?

870
00:47:15.310 --> 00:47:17.150
You saw what just happened
to the Martian ship.

871
00:47:17.225 --> 00:47:19.837
We may be able to use it
to send us back to our time.

872
00:47:20.011 --> 00:47:22.032
The antimatter explosion.
combined with the explosion

873
00:47:22.056 --> 00:47:24.078
of the planet's core.
has created the necessary energy

874
00:47:24.102 --> 00:47:26.102
to free <i>Enterprise</i>
from this temporal anchor point.

875
00:47:26.191 --> 00:47:27.888
snapping
the quantum entanglement

876
00:47:28.062 --> 00:47:29.629
back to the exact point
we came from.

877
00:47:29.803 --> 00:47:31.979
Before the blast wave
tears our ship apart?

878
00:47:32.153 --> 00:47:33.546
Unknown.

879
00:47:33.894 --> 00:47:37.289
But it is our only option
if we intend to go home.

880
00:47:38.943 --> 00:47:40.770
Erica. come about.

881
00:47:40.945 --> 00:47:42.947
Take us straight
into the blast wave.

882
00:47:43.121 --> 00:47:45.732
Spock. if you have any
calculations. now's the time.

883
00:47:46.515 --> 00:47:48.996
Helm. come to course 1-4-7.
mark 2.

884
00:47:50.998 --> 00:47:52.347
Roger that.

885
00:47:52.521 --> 00:47:55.655
Everybody. hang on to something.

886
00:47:55.829 --> 00:47:57.135
Anything.

887
00:47:58.745 --> 00:48:00.355
Everything.

888
00:48:54.453 --> 00:48:56.020
After running
multiple simulations.

889
00:48:56.194 --> 00:48:58.413
I determined that a fragment
from the Dol'drm planet

890
00:48:58.587 --> 00:49:00.154
is the Chicxulub asteroid.

891
00:49:00.328 --> 00:49:02.287
<i>The</i> one that hit Earth

892
00:49:02.461 --> 00:49:03.897
65 million years ago?

893
00:49:04.245 --> 00:49:07.596
And led to the extinction
of the dinosaurs.

894
00:49:07.770 --> 00:49:09.076
Does that mean...

895
00:49:09.337 --> 00:49:10.469
Yes.

896
00:49:10.773 --> 00:49:12.775
The remaining debris.
less than four percent

897
00:49:12.950 --> 00:49:14.212
of the planet's original mass.

898
00:49:14.386 --> 00:49:16.066
eventually became part
of the asteroid belt

899
00:49:16.170 --> 00:49:17.606
as we have come to know it.

900
00:49:17.780 --> 00:49:19.260
Furthermore.
the absence of the planet

901
00:49:19.347 --> 00:49:20.947
caused a gravimetric shift
in the system.

902
00:49:21.088 --> 00:49:22.742
moving Mars
further from the sun.

903
00:49:22.916 --> 00:49:25.832
Its atmosphere cooled to become
the Mars we know today.

904
00:49:26.006 --> 00:49:29.749
Earth also cooled.
ushering in the Cenozoic Era.

905
00:49:29.923 --> 00:49:31.620
and eventually...

906
00:49:31.794 --> 00:49:33.971
The evolution of humanity.

907
00:49:36.103 --> 00:49:39.411
Even I remember a part of that.

908
00:49:39.672 --> 00:49:41.979
So. we only exist

909
00:49:42.153 --> 00:49:45.330
because of what we did?

910
00:49:45.504 --> 00:49:48.898
I think we might exist
because of what we didn't do.

911
00:49:49.073 --> 00:49:52.380
The Martians
had to take our weapons.

912
00:49:52.554 --> 00:49:56.645
And we had to let them destroy
the Dol'drm planet.

913
00:49:57.995 --> 00:50:00.127
Because they always have.

914
00:50:01.563 --> 00:50:03.174
We were always there.

915
00:50:04.349 --> 00:50:06.481
So we were never in danger
of changing anything?

916
00:50:06.655 --> 00:50:08.353
O-Or were we?

917
00:50:08.527 --> 00:50:10.050
What about Commander Cassell?

918
00:50:10.224 --> 00:50:13.184
Did she destroy her own planet?

919
00:50:19.451 --> 00:50:21.018
I think...

920
00:50:21.801 --> 00:50:23.803
we could all use a night off.

921
00:50:25.935 --> 00:50:28.155
Yeah. I heard it.

922
00:50:28.329 --> 00:50:30.070
Let's go before
he changes his mind.

923
00:50:30.244 --> 00:50:32.159
Mm-hmm.

924
00:50:32.333 --> 00:50:34.205
You're all dismissed.

925
00:50:37.773 --> 00:50:39.166
Thank you.

926
00:50:48.175 --> 00:50:50.830
Commander Cassell.

927
00:50:53.441 --> 00:50:54.961
She just wanted
to save her own people.

928
00:50:55.095 --> 00:50:57.793
I would have done
exactly the same thing.

929
00:50:57.967 --> 00:50:59.534
And now they're all gone.

930
00:50:59.795 --> 00:51:02.494
without a trace
of their ever having existed.

931
00:51:02.755 --> 00:51:05.192
Not entirely.

932
00:51:06.802 --> 00:51:10.371
I ran Cassell's DNA
through our database.

933
00:51:11.111 --> 00:51:13.070
It appears that Martian DNA
is present

934
00:51:13.244 --> 00:51:16.073
in innumerable species
throughout the galaxy.

935
00:51:16.247 --> 00:51:17.770
They escaped?

936
00:51:17.944 --> 00:51:19.380
Some. at least.

937
00:51:19.641 --> 00:51:22.209
The commander
may not have survived.

938
00:51:22.383 --> 00:51:23.906
but her people did.

939
00:51:24.081 --> 00:51:26.344
And the Dol'drm?

940
00:51:27.823 --> 00:51:32.001
If their planet
had remained in the system.

941
00:51:32.176 --> 00:51:35.962
entire histories
would be erased.

942
00:51:36.136 --> 00:51:38.921
Trillions of lives.

943
00:51:40.140 --> 00:51:42.447
Evolutions undone.

944
00:51:42.621 --> 00:51:44.405
Yeah. but...

945
00:51:46.015 --> 00:51:49.106
I didn't know that in the moment
that I made that call.

946
00:51:51.630 --> 00:51:54.241
It was a hunch...
it was a good one. but...

947
00:51:54.415 --> 00:51:55.851
but I had no data.

948
00:51:56.025 --> 00:51:59.290
You. more than anyone
that I know.

949
00:51:59.464 --> 00:52:03.294
have thought about the past
and the future a great deal.

950
00:52:05.296 --> 00:52:07.994
But most of us live in the now.

951
00:52:10.083 --> 00:52:11.606
I guess...

952
00:52:12.607 --> 00:52:15.654
never slowing down.
never stopping...

953
00:52:17.395 --> 00:52:20.093
it's been quieter
than being in my head.

954
00:52:20.963 --> 00:52:23.966
A bit of unsolicited advice.

955
00:52:26.534 --> 00:52:29.189
Find a way to make peace
with both.

956
00:52:46.032 --> 00:52:48.861
<i>A Princess of Mars.</i>

957
00:52:49.688 --> 00:52:51.690
Who knew that book
would be so prophetic?

958
00:52:54.040 --> 00:52:56.347
"I have ever been prone
to seek adventure

959
00:52:56.608 --> 00:52:59.045
"and to investigate
and experiment.

960
00:52:59.219 --> 00:53:03.180
where wiser men would have
left well enough alone."

961
00:53:05.573 --> 00:53:07.358
Love this book.

962
00:53:08.402 --> 00:53:10.162
My father... he-he always
laughed at the idea

963
00:53:10.404 --> 00:53:13.451
of Martians existing
before Federation terraforming.

964
00:53:14.626 --> 00:53:17.716
Ugh. if I could just go back
and tell him now.

965
00:53:17.890 --> 00:53:21.198
I think one time-travel
adventure a day is enough.

966
00:53:21.372 --> 00:53:24.418
And this one needs
to stay a secret.

967
00:53:24.592 --> 00:53:25.941
Thought you'd say that.

968
00:53:26.246 --> 00:53:27.658
Well. if it were up to me.
everyone would know

969
00:53:27.682 --> 00:53:29.007
that the <i>Enterprise</i>
was responsible

970
00:53:29.031 --> 00:53:30.424
for humanity's origin.

971
00:53:30.729 --> 00:53:33.122
But the Federation Council
might want us to pause

972
00:53:33.297 --> 00:53:36.256
before we rush in
to amend history books.

973
00:53:36.430 --> 00:53:38.215
So. what do we say?

974
00:53:39.041 --> 00:53:40.478
The truth.

975
00:53:41.261 --> 00:53:44.003
We lost contact with your ship
for a few moments.

976
00:53:44.264 --> 00:53:47.572
Then the solar storm collapsed.
exploded and vanished.

977
00:53:47.746 --> 00:53:51.228
By the time the ensuing
gamma-ray burst had dissipated.

978
00:53:51.402 --> 00:53:54.318
communication with the
<i>Enterprise</i> was reestablished.

979
00:53:54.579 --> 00:53:56.668
And what about...

980
00:53:57.495 --> 00:54:01.238
us answering our own Mayday

981
00:54:01.412 --> 00:54:06.939
from a subspace buoy we deployed
65 million years ago?

982
00:54:07.113 --> 00:54:09.898
One sent here
by a storm that we created

983
00:54:10.072 --> 00:54:13.554
after it sent us back in time.

984
00:54:15.817 --> 00:54:17.297
Chris.

985
00:54:17.471 --> 00:54:19.517
everything happened
as it was meant to.

986
00:54:19.691 --> 00:54:22.084
That much is clear.

987
00:54:22.259 --> 00:54:23.782
So don't overthink it.

988
00:54:26.393 --> 00:54:28.221
What about the promotion?

989
00:54:28.395 --> 00:54:31.137
Hmm? Had any time to consider?

990
00:54:32.573 --> 00:54:35.402
Yeah.

991
00:54:35.576 --> 00:54:37.448
I saw the past.
present and future

992
00:54:37.709 --> 00:54:41.669
in a way that I never
thought possible.

993
00:54:43.323 --> 00:54:45.369
I want to focus on my now.

994
00:54:45.543 --> 00:54:49.111
and that's here with <i>Enterprise.</i>

995
00:54:49.286 --> 00:54:51.592
I'm not ready for the promotion.

996
00:54:53.115 --> 00:54:54.856
But...

997
00:54:55.770 --> 00:54:57.990
I know someone else who is.

998
00:54:58.817 --> 00:55:01.123
I... That's...

999
00:55:01.907 --> 00:55:03.169
Chris.

1000
00:55:03.430 --> 00:55:06.346
Eh. you don't have
to say anything.

1001
00:55:06.520 --> 00:55:08.522
So I'll say it.

1002
00:55:08.696 --> 00:55:12.570
To Commander Una Chin-Riley.

1003
00:55:12.744 --> 00:55:14.064
Congratulations
on your promotion.

1004
00:55:14.223 --> 00:55:16.051
You more than deserve it.

1005
00:55:16.225 --> 00:55:18.184
One step closer to captain

1006
00:55:18.358 --> 00:55:21.448
and your own starship.

1007
00:55:25.800 --> 00:55:27.149
Cadet.

1008
00:55:27.324 --> 00:55:28.934
I wanted to see
how you're feeling

1009
00:55:29.108 --> 00:55:32.111
after your first real adventure
on the <i>Enterprise.</i>

1010
00:55:32.285 --> 00:55:35.157
I have learned that Starfleet
is not what I expected.

1011
00:55:35.332 --> 00:55:37.551
Oh. it can surprise you.

1012
00:55:37.725 --> 00:55:40.293
My family was disappointed
that I was not placed

1013
00:55:40.554 --> 00:55:41.947
at the Vulcan Science Academy.

1014
00:55:42.208 --> 00:55:44.819
I thought this would be
a good alternative.

1015
00:55:44.993 --> 00:55:46.908
Well. it very well could be.

1016
00:55:47.082 --> 00:55:48.519
It is not.

1017
00:55:48.780 --> 00:55:51.260
I now understand why
my parents were disappointed.

1018
00:55:51.435 --> 00:55:52.653
This is a chaotic place.

1019
00:55:52.958 --> 00:55:55.003
It likely helps that Spock
is part human.

1020
00:55:55.177 --> 00:55:56.614
I. however. am not.

1021
00:55:56.788 --> 00:55:58.485
Thank you
for your questions. Ensign.

1022
00:55:58.659 --> 00:56:01.314
but any further
are not necessary.

1023
00:56:05.100 --> 00:56:06.100
Honestly?

1024
00:56:06.232 --> 00:56:08.495
She might just be very Vulcan.

1025
00:56:08.669 --> 00:56:10.192
That's all.

1026
00:56:10.367 --> 00:56:12.630
It's gonna be a long year.

1027
00:56:12.804 --> 00:56:15.720
Come on. La'An and Una and I
are gonna talk about dinosaurs.

1028
00:56:15.894 --> 00:56:18.070
Way more worth your time.

1029
00:56:21.334 --> 00:56:22.422
Scotty.

1030
00:56:22.596 --> 00:56:24.816
Are you gonna...

1031
00:56:25.686 --> 00:56:27.253
Say sorry?

1032
00:56:27.471 --> 00:56:29.536
You wrench jockeys are kind of
sensitive. aren't you?

1033
00:56:29.560 --> 00:56:31.300
Frickin' engineers.

1034
00:56:31.562 --> 00:56:33.477
Bloody pilots.

1035
00:56:45.314 --> 00:56:47.229
So...

1036
00:56:47.404 --> 00:56:50.537
are you guys gonna tell us
about the dinosaurs?

1037
00:56:50.711 --> 00:56:51.711
Oh. yeah.

1038
00:56:53.758 --> 00:56:55.586
Come on.

1039
00:56:58.850 --> 00:57:03.855
It was... something.

1040
00:57:05.987 --> 00:57:09.121
<i>We've seen a lot
of strange new worlds.</i>

1041
00:57:09.295 --> 00:57:13.560
<i>but we'll never see something
like this again.</i>

1042
00:58:13.098 --> 00:58:16.884
